07550nam a22008775i 9780271032214DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212002pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710322147 a10.1515/97802710322142doi  a(DE-B1597)583633  a(OCoLC)1262308163  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aB318.M48bD64 2002eb 7aPHI0260002bisacsh04a183/.222200aDoes Socrates Have a Method? :bRethinking the Elenchus in Plato's Dialogues and Beyond /ced. by Gary Alan Scott. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAbbreviations for Plato's Dialogues -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tContributors -- tPart One: Historical Origins of Socratic Method -- t1 Parmenidean Elenchos -- t2 Forensic Characteristics of Socratic Argumentation -- t3 Elenchos and Exetasis: Capturing the Purpose of Socratic Interrogation -- t4 Comments on Lesher, Ausland, and Tarrant -- tPart Two: Reexamining Vlastos's Analysis of "the Elenchus" -- t5 Variety of Socratic Elenchi -- t6 Problems with Socratic Method -- t7 Elenctic Interpretation and the Delphic Oracle -- t8 The Socratic Elenchos? -- tPart Three: Socratic Argumentation and Interrogation in Specific Dialogues -- tA. Clitophon, Euthydemus, Lysis, Philebus -- t9 The Socratic Elenchus as Constructive Protreptic -- t10 Humbling as Upbringing: The Ethical Dimension of the Elenchus in the Lysis -- t11 The (De)construction of Irrefutable Argument in Plato's Philebus -- t12 Elenchos, Protreptic, and Platonic Philosophizing -- tB. Four Interpretations of Elenchus in the Charmides -- t13 Socratic Dialectic in the Charmides -- t14 The Elenchos in the Charmides, 162-175 -- t15 Certainty and Consistency in the Socratic Elenchus -- t16 Questioning the Self: A Reaction to Carvalho, Press, and Schmid -- tAbout the Contributors -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough ";the Socratic method"; is commonly understood as a style of pedagogy involving cross-questioning between teacher and student, there has long been debate among scholars of ancient philosophy about how this method as attributed to Socrates should be defined or, indeed, whether Socrates can be said to have used any single, uniform method at all distinctive to his way of philosophizing. This volume brings together essays by classicists and philosophers examining this controversy anew. The point of departure for many of those engaged in the debate has been the identification of Socratic method with ";the elenchus"; as a technique of logical argumentation aimed at refuting an interlocutor, which Gregory Vlastos highlighted in an influential article in 1983. The essays in this volume look again at many of the issues to which Vlastos drew attention but also seek to broaden the discussion well beyond the limits of his formulation. Some contributors question the suitability of the elenchus as a general description of how Socrates engages his interlocutors; others trace the historical origins of the kinds of argumentation Socrates employs; others explore methods in addition to the elenchus that Socrates uses; several propose new ways of thinking about Socratic practices. Eight essays focus on specific dialogues, each examining why Plato has Socrates use the particular methods he does in the context defined by the dialogue. Overall, representing a wide range of approaches in Platonic scholarship, the volume aims to enliven and reorient the debate over Socratic method so as to set a new agenda for future research. Contributors are Hayden W. Ausland, Hugh H. Benson, Thomas C. Brickhouse, Michelle Carpenter, John M. Carvalho, Lloyd P. Gerson, Francisco J. Gonzalez, James H. Lesher, Mark McPherran, Ronald M. Polansky, Gerald A. Press, François Renaud, and W. Thomas Schmid, Nicholas D. Smith, P. Christopher Smith, Harold Tarrant, Joanne B. Waugh, and Charles M. Young.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMethodologyxHistory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAusland, Hayden, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenson, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrickhouse, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarpenter, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarvalho, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerson, Lloyd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzalez, Francisco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLesher, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcPherran, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPolansky, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPress, Gerald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRenaud, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmid, W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScott, Gary Alan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aScott, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTarrant, Harold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaugh, Joanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYoung, Charles, econtributor.4c